<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE58FFE6FF3FF6C3FC544971" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE58FFE6FF3FF6C3FEA548EB" blockId="6.[189,311,1180,1206]" box="[189,311,1180,1206]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE58FFE6FF3FF6C3FEA548EB" bold="true" box="[189,311,1180,1206]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE58FFE6FF3FF6C3FEA548EB" bold="true" box="[189,311,1180,1206]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE58FFE6FF3FF694FC544971" blockId="6.[189,1399,1227,1324]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Unilaminar encrusting colonies with rhomboidal to oval autozooids; opesia oval to subtriangular, extensive finely granular cryptocyst, small elongate avicularia placed on raised cystid randomly located in the narrow interzooecial space. Ovicells endozooecial, cap like.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
