<paragraph id="8B883076DE58FFE8FF3FF56FFACC4D1B" blockId="6.[188,1399,1840,1972]" lastBlockId="8.[189,1398,265,327]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">
Colony unilaminar, encrusting. Autozooids oval to lozenge-shaped, separated by shallow, thin grooves (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE58FFE6FF44F50CFEB64B30" box="[198,292,1875,1901]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-95@7.[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Antropora ramaniaensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 0440). A. General view of the colony showing rhomboidal to oval autozooids. B. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids with extensive cryptocyst and interzooecial avicularia. C. Close-up of autozooids with cap like, endozooecial ovicells (arrow) and interzooecial avicularia. D. Close-up of autozooids with the endozooecial ovicells." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580792/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Gymnocyst vestigial; cryptocyst extensive, finely granular, gently sloping into opesia. Opesia roughly oval to bell shaped given the later constrictions, narrowing distally, occupying ½ of frontal area (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE58FFE6FF47F5C6FED64BE9" box="[197,324,1945,1972]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-95@7.[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Antropora ramaniaensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 0440). A. General view of the colony showing rhomboidal to oval autozooids. B. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids with extensive cryptocyst and interzooecial avicularia. C. Close-up of autozooids with cap like, endozooecial ovicells (arrow) and interzooecial avicularia. D. Close-up of autozooids with the endozooecial ovicells." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580792/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Fig. 4B–C</figureCitation>
). Distal zooidal margins arched, raised. Small interzooecial avicularia elongate, with rounded rostrum, mostly distally directed, without crossbar, avicularium raised on small cystid seated randomly in narrow interzooidal space. Ovicells endozooecial, cap like, observed in fertile zooids (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE56FFE8FB52F373FAC34D1B" box="[1232,1361,300,326]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-95@7.[215,1373,692,1854]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Antropora ramaniaensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 0440). A. General view of the colony showing rhomboidal to oval autozooids. B. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids with extensive cryptocyst and interzooecial avicularia. C. Close-up of autozooids with cap like, endozooecial ovicells (arrow) and interzooecial avicularia. D. Close-up of autozooids with the endozooecial ovicells." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580792" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580792/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Fig. 4C–D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
