<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE56FFE8FF3FF331FC574F9A" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE56FFE8FF3FF331FEA24DD5" blockId="8.[189,304,366,392]" box="[189,304,366,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE56FFE8FF3FF331FEA24DD5" bold="true" box="[189,304,366,392]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FF3FF331FEA24DD5" bold="true" box="[189,304,366,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE56FFE8FF3FF3C3FC574F9A" blockId="8.[185,1400,412,967]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">
The circum-tropical Recent species 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE56FFE8FDDFF3C3FC4B4DEB" authority="(Hincks, 1880)" baseAuthorityName="Hincks" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[605,985,412,438]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Antroporidae" genus="Antropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FDDFF3C3FCB74DEB" box="[605,805,412,438]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Antropora minor</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FCB1F3C3FC434DEB" author="Hincks T." box="[819,977,412,438]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" refId="ref7942" refString="Hincks T. 1880. A history of the British Marine Polyzoa. Van Voorst, London. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 31555" type="book" year="1880">Hincks, 1880</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is similar to the Kachchh species in the shape of autozooids and opesia but differs in having a coarsely granular cryptocyst, the presence of small kenozooidal papillae at the proximal end of the autozooid and the occurrence of large vicarious avicularia (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FF73F059FE554E7D" author="Tilbrook K. J." box="[241,455,518,544]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="25 - 49" refId="ref8756" refString="Tilbrook K. J. 1998. The species of Antropora Norman, 1903 (Bryozoa: Cheilostomatida), with the description of a new genus in the Calloporoidea. Records of the South Australian Museum 31: 25 - 49." type="journal article" year="1998">Tilbrook 1998: 34</bibRefCitation>
, fig 2a–f). 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE56FFE8FDC5F059FB884E7D" authority="Canu &amp; Bassler, 1928" authorityName="Canu &amp; Bassler" authorityYear="1928" box="[583,1050,518,544]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Antroporidae" genus="Antropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="typica">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FDC5F059FC834E7D" box="[583,785,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Antropora typica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FC9AF059FB884E7D" author="Canu F. &amp; Bassler R. S." box="[792,1050,518,544]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref7014" refString="Canu F. &amp; Bassler R. S. 1928. Les bryozoaires du Maroc et de Mauritanie, 2 me memoire. Memoires de la Societe des Sciences naturelles du Maroc 18: 1 - 85." type="journal article" year="1928">Canu &amp; Bassler, 1928</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has a superficial resemblance with the Kachchh species in its general morphology; however, the former species is characterized by smoothly calcified gymnocysts, interzooecial avicularia with an acutely triangular rostrum, and sporadic large vicarious avicularia (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FDA3F030FD6A4ED4" author="Tilbrook K. J." box="[545,760,623,649]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="25 - 49" refId="ref8756" refString="Tilbrook K. J. 1998. The species of Antropora Norman, 1903 (Bryozoa: Cheilostomatida), with the description of a new genus in the Calloporoidea. Records of the South Australian Museum 31: 25 - 49." type="journal article" year="1998">Tilbrook 1998: 37</bibRefCitation>
, figs 1f, 3a). 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE56FFE8FC0DF02FFAD24ED4" authority="Marcus, 1937" authorityName="Marcus" authorityYear="1937" box="[911,1344,623,650]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Antroporidae" genus="Antropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="leucocypha">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FC0DF02FFB0A4ED4" box="[911,1176,623,650]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Antropora leucocypha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FB1DF02FFAD24ED4" author="Marcus E." box="[1183,1344,623,650]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="5 - 224" refId="ref8003" refString="Marcus E. 1937. Bryozoarios marinhos brasileiros I. Boletim da Faculdade de filosofia, ciencias e letras, Universidade di Sao Paolo, Zoologia 1: 5 - 224. https: // doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2526 - 4877. bsffclzoologia. 1937.113912" type="journal article" year="1937">Marcus, 1937</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
also resembles the new Kachchh species in the shape of the autozooid (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FC79F0CDFB4F4EF0" author="Winston J. E." box="[1019,1245,658,685]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="99 - 176" refId="ref8950" refString="Winston J. E. 1982. Marine Bryozoans (Ectoprocta) of the Indian River area (Florida). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 173: 99 - 176." type="journal article" year="1982">Winston 1982: 123</bibRefCitation>
, figs 36–37). However, the former has a beaded and crenulated cryptocyst and autozooids surrounded by numerous kenozooids. The Recent cosmopolitan warm-water species 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE56FFE8FC01F086FB464EAE" authority="Hincks, 1880" authorityName="Hincks" authorityYear="1880" box="[899,1236,729,755]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Antroporidae" genus="Antropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="granulifera">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FC01F086FBBF4EAE" box="[899,1069,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">A. granulifera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FBB7F086FB464EAE" author="Hincks T." box="[1077,1236,729,755]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" refId="ref7942" refString="Hincks T. 1880. A history of the British Marine Polyzoa. Van Voorst, London. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 31555" type="book" year="1880">Hincks, 1880</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the crenulated, raised mural rim and shows a similarity in the shape of the autozooids. The Indonesian late Burdigalian species 
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FE2BF17FFE504F67" box="[425,450,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">A.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FE6CF140FD064F64" box="[494,660,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">subvespertilio</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FD21F140FC344F64" author="Canu F. &amp; Bassler R. S." box="[675,934,799,825]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 685" refId="ref7052" refString="Canu F. &amp; Bassler R. S. 1929. Bryozoa of the Philippine region. United States National Museum Bulletin 100: 1 - 685." type="journal article" year="1929">Canu &amp; Bassler, 1929</bibRefCitation>
) differs in having a trifoliate opesia and differently shaped autozooids (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE56FFE8FDD0F11DFC244F00" author="Di Martino E. &amp; Taylor P. D." box="[594,950,834,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" pagination="17 - 126" refId="ref7167" refString="Di Martino E. &amp; Taylor P. D. 2014. Miocene Bryozoa from East Kalimantan, Indonesia. Part 1: Cyclostomata and ' Anascan' Cheilostomata. Scripta Geologica 146: 17 - 126." type="journal article" year="2014">Di Martino &amp; Taylor 2014: 43</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 15, fig. 2a–e). 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE56FFE8FB0FF11CFD9A4FDC" authority="Guha &amp; Gopikrishna, 2005" authorityName="Guha &amp; Gopikrishna" authorityYear="2005" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Antroporidae" genus="Antropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="8" pageNumber="24" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="gadhavii">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE56FFE8FB0FF11CFAE54F01" box="[1165,1399,834,861]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="24">Antropora gadhavii</emphasis>
Guha &amp; Gopikrishna, 2005
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
